<html><head><meta http-equiv="Content-Type" content="text/html; charset=utf-8" /><meta http-equiv="Content-Style-Type" content="text/css" /><meta name="generator" content="Aspose.Words for .NET 13.4.0.0" /><title>June 1, 2006</title></head><body><div><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 72pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:36pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Written evidence submitted by DAI </span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">In response to your request for input from the DFID contractor community into the International Development Committee inquiry into the DFID annual report, DAI</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">, a global development company working with a wide number of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">bilateral</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">, multilateral and the public and private sectors, </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">is pleased to submit the following comments.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> We have responded only to those areas where we feel we have something to contribute. </span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Summary</span></p><ul type="square" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">DFID is seen as one of the most effective bilaterals.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Development aid needs a radical rethink to address a fast changing world, reflected in greater competences and capacity in developing countries with greater economic growth. DFID should lead that debate with its clients. </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Development needs to move from the volume of aid delivered, to its quality and effectiveness and better leverage to give greater input.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">The value of multilateral aid needs better scrutiny. Do we still need multilateral agencies designed for the problems of the last century?</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">DFID is perceived to be weaker technically than in the past. </span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">At the country level DFID needs deeper skills in programme management, less turnover and needs to avoid a tendency to micro-manage.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Procurement and contracting frameworks remain costly.</span></li><li style="font-family:Wingdings; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 9.58pt; padding-left:4.62pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">DFID needs to develop consistency and understanding of output based contracting.</span></li></ul><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">General Comments </span></p><ol type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Development approaches are in need of a radical rethink. As a key donor and a respected bilateral, DFID should be challenged to lead that new thinking and respond to the ever-increasing pace of change in development. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="2" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Overall, we see DFID as one of the most effective bilaterals, with a strong global brand and reputation. However, in the fast-changing world of development—manifested in growing developing-world economies, more sophisticated and substantial national budgets, and increasing capacity in developing countries (in public, private, and civil society sectors)—the future role of a traditional bilateral such as DFID is neither clear nor clearly articulated. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">With the United Kingdom and other countries meeting their 0.7% target, the quality of deve</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">lopment assistance </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">now assume</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">s</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> more importance than its quantity.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> How the United Kingdom maximizes the impact of its development assistance and leverages that impact to achieve U.K. national objectives, at a time when development finance is in relative decline compared to other sources of finance, is the real post-2015 challenge. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="3" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">As members of the development community, we must be frank in acknowledging that we are all part of a global development industry, employing many tens of thousands of people in western countries and responsible for the best possible use of billions of dollars in development assistance. We all have vested interests of one kind or another, and some institutions have only a limited interest in fundamentally adapting to meet the fast pace of change in the developing world.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="4" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Whilst DFID remains influential in high-level strategic circles, for example in the UN Secretary General’s High Level Panel, at the next level down DFID is seen as less effective and engaged. The department’s intellectual and technical underpinning seems to have weakened. DFID appears under-represented in important fora, as compared to years past, and DFID officials advise privately that they lack the travel budget and administrative support to meet those obligations. Nor does it appear that DFID has strengthened its operations (see below). Both factors are </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">of concern</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">, especially</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> with so much </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">DFID</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">’s</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> budget going to multilaterals.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">Trends in DFID's expenditure and total UK ODA, including</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">the split between bilateral and multilateral expenditure</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">/</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">administration expenditure</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> </span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="5" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Clearly, DFID should maintain an appropriate balance between bilateral and multilateral spend. But while some progress has been made, DFID’s limited capacity to assess multilateral effectiveness—let alone its capacity to </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">improve the</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">ir</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> effectiveness</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> where performance is lacking—remains a concern. It is encouraging to see funding stopped to those multilateral partners that significantly underperform, but too often development finance continues to flow to multilaterals that are perceived to be of limited effectiveness. It is time to ask some radical questions: Why do we continue to support institutions that may have historical relevance but no longer, perhaps, have the same role or mandate, or no longer deliver impact commensurate with their costs? If greater impact and value for money could be achieved through, say, a re-allocation of resources to the country level, should such institutions continue to exist? It is time we had that debate, and that DFID take a leading role in it.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt; orphans:0; text-align:justify; widows:0"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">DFID's ability to meet the 0.7% target and the implications for the future</span><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">; Managing spend through contractors, multilaterals and NGOs</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="6" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">DFID has met and </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">should </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">be able </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">to continue to meet its 0.7% target. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">The issue</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">, as noted above, is not </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">the volume of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">development finance, but </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">the quality, accountability</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> and impact of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">that expenditure, and the leverage it affords</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> The risk we face is that in order to meet its target spend, DFID may push through spending in the wrong areas, or favour funding for global institutions that have the capacity to “absorb” such volumes and offer easy-to-measure impact, but do not reflect the true priorities of the poor at country level. Equally important is how spending decisions are communicated to the public, particularly as we move from relatively straightforward, quick, and readily understood development wins (such as in child health) to address more fundamental, complex, long-term development objectives. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="7" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">DFID does not have the in-house capacity to directly manage and deliver aid spending. It needs better technical skills and greater management capacity to manage that process through others. When the recipient and implementer of those funds is a foreign government, funded through budget support, or a global institution, the degree of control over the aid spend is in question, and the funds will not always deliver the expected development impact. In some cases, other U.K. Government departments may have skills more relevant to the development purpose at hand than DFID. For example, when it comes to building health systems, the Department of Health is better placed than DFID, given capabilities in the NHS. The problems of a Minister of Health in Rwanda are increasingly </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">similar to those of her counterpart Minister in Britain: how to control spend, maximise benefit, share the financing burdens, and so on. Can DFID work better with other U.K. government departments and  private sector actors to meet those increasingly common challenges with world-class technical expertise?</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">On</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> w</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">hether DFID's current staffing levels are adequate, whether staff have the right skills</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">,</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> and whether length of postings </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">is</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold"> appropriate</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="8" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Staffing levels in DFID missions overseas are generally adequate to plan programming and oversee implementation.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">We feel that the mixture between administrative and technical staff is generally appropriate as well.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Nonetheless, there is room for development in three areas.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="9" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 12.5pt; padding-left:1.7pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">First, DFID can develop project management as a discipline in its own right.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">This would enable DFID staff to better support implementing agencies (cooperating ministries, NGOs, contractors, etc.).</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> DFID staff would benefit from skills development in</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> large</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">scale project management</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">, with an emphasis on</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> planning, flexibility, responsiveness, budget management, risk management, and evaluation</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">. </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">The recent Programme Management Review and the appointment of a Head of Profession for Programme Management are both positive steps in this regard.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">However</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">,</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> the Programme Management Review was perhaps not sufficiently ambitious as </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">it </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">concentrate</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">d</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> on easy wins and readily achievabl</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">e</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> improvements, rather than</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> taking on</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> more fundamental </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">issues of</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> staff development and advancement.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">To give project management skills a more central place in DFID’s tool kit will require a more </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">thorough</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> examination of staff development priorities and the career paths for DFID staff.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="10" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Second, whilst turnover </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">of</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> DFID staff </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">as they </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">rotate between postings is inevitable, we feel that transitions between programme managers and technical advisors can be managed more actively.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Frequently there is little or no overlap between outgoing and incoming staff in a given position.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">This </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">lapse in continuity </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">can result in significant inconsistencies and changes in strategy mid-project.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="11" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Third, junior programme managers are often unable to make decisions. They compensate by micro-managing contractors, NGOs, and others on issues of relatively minor importance, which is burdensome and counter-productive. </span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="12" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Finally, the linkage between central policy making and strategy </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">development </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">and </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">subsequent </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">policy implementation at the country office level can be significantly improved.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">New initiatives, such as the drive toward output</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">-</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">based contracting, have not always been well or widely explained to the staff responsible for managing projects at the country level.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> This disconnect is not an easy problem to solve but doing so is critical to ensuring that DFID is consistently delivering on its strategy and also supporting the drive to achieve value for money—which remains poorly understood across the organisation and requires new thinking at the country office level</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">if new commercial approaches are to realise their undoubted promise.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">On DFID's ability to spend the large increase in its 2013-</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">20</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-weight:bold">14 budget efficiently and effectively</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="13" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Inevitably, DFID has had to increase the average size of projects in order to scale-up impact in a cost-efficient way. This approach is often entirely appropriate </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">as more ambitious targets are set.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> However, implementing it will </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">require</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">increase</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">d attention to</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">the functional areas of </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">procurement </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">and project management.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="14" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">One of the innovations introduced to help with the management of larger and more frequent and flexible procurements has been the use of contracting frameworks. This tool has the potential to speed procurement without harming the quality of the process, and to allow DFID to reduce the cost of procurement significantly.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><ol start="15" type="1" style="margin:0pt; padding-left:0pt"><li style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:0pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">However, t</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">he frameworks are not being used </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">in the right way</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> </span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">Where bidders have been preselected, more and faster procurement should be carried out than is currently the case.</span><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt"> Single frameworks should not be split into separate lots, as this creates marketplace confusion and adds to the time and cost that bidders must invest in creating bidding arrangements under a framework call down. Also, DFID is openly encouraging small and medium-sized enterprises (SMEs) that have joined a framework consortium to break their teaming agreements in order to create a more open market for the smaller specialist organisations. While this will benefit them in the short run, it calls into question the framework process as a whole. Larger contractors with the capacity to manage large projects will not be interested in involving SMEs in project implementation if there is no market advantage to them in partnering. At a minimum, if DFID does not want to see consortia developed under the frameworks, this should be made clear in the tendering documents, so that market participants do not invest time and money in developing consortia in the first place, thereby driving up bidding costs ultimately borne by DFID.</span></li></ol><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt 0pt 0pt 14.2pt; text-align:justify; text-indent:-14.2pt"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt; font-style:italic">October 2013</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="line-height:12pt; margin:0pt; text-align:justify"><span style="font-family:Times; font-size:10pt">&#xa0;</span></p><p style="margin:0pt"><span style="font-family:'Times New Roman'; font-size:12pt">&#xa0;</span></p></div></body></html>